1: Greatest Common Divisor (GCD)

check positive integers (helper function)

pseudocode

  • input: x (a number)
  • convert x to integer and test if the integer value equals to original x
  • test if x is positive
  • output:
  • if both conditions are TRUE, then return TRUE, the number x is a positive integer;
  • elsereturn FALSE, the number x is not a positive integer

gcd function

pseudocode

  • inputs: two given values a, b
  • test if a, b are numeric
  • if not numeric, stop the program and return error message
  • test if a, b are positive integers
  • if not positive integers, stop the program and return error message
  • Repeat:
  • assign original a to old_a
    • old_a <- a
  • assign original b to a
    • a <- b
  • divide old_a by b and store the resulted remainder to b
    • b <- old_a %% b
  • test if b == 0;
    • if no, repeat above steps again
    • if yes, stop the process
  • output: a
#test the gcd function
gcd(1071, 462)
## [1] 21
gcd(462, 1071)
## [1] 21
gcd(646, 1406)
## [1] 38
gcd(1, 10)
## [1] 1
#test error handling
try(gcd(0, 12))
## Error in gcd(0, 12) : The inputs are not positive integers!
try(gcd(4.5, 12))
## Error in gcd(4.5, 12) : The inputs are not positive integers!
try(gcd(-1, 12))
## Error in gcd(-1, 12) : The inputs are not positive integers!

gcd_3 function

pseudocode

  • inputs: three given value a, b, c
  • use gcd function to find greatest common divisor between first two numbers, a and b, and store the resulted gcd in gcd_temp
  • gcd_temp <- gcd(a, b)
  • use gcd function to find greatest common divisor between gcd_temp and c
  • gcd(gcd_temp, c)
  • output: gcd(gcd_temp, c)
#test the gcd_3 function
gcd_3(1071, 462, 4452)
## [1] 21
gcd_3(646, 1406, 4218)
## [1] 38

2: Prime Factorization

is_prime function (helper function)

pseudocode

  • input: a given vector x containing a list of numbers
  • create an empty vector called to store result
  • result_vector <- NULL *for every number inside the vector:
  • if number < 2 (since 2 is the smallest prime, any number less than 2 is not prime)
    • result_vector <- c(result_vector, FALSE)
  • else if check_positive_integer(num) == FALSE (since all prime numbers are positive integers)
    • result_vector <- c(result_vector, FALSE)
  • else
    • factor_num <- 0 (factor_num indicates the number of factors the number has other than itself)
    • take square root of the number and round down, store the result in k
    • for j = 1 to k
    • if number %% j
      • factor_num <- factor_num + 1
  • if factor_num == 1 (prime number should only be divisible by 1 in this case)
    • result_vector <- c(result_vector, TRUE)
  • else
    • result_vector <- c(result_vector, FALSE)
  • output: result_vector (which is a logical vector containning TRUE or FALSE)
#test the is_prime function
is_prime(9)
## [1] FALSE
is_prime(c(2, 97, 23, 51, 119, -1, 0, 1.5))
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
x <- sample(x = 1e4, size=1)
y <- get_factors(x)
this_works <- prod(y) == x & all(is_prime(y))
this_works
## [1] TRUE
#is_prime function works!

get_factors function

pseudocode

  • input: x (a given value)
  • test if x is numeric
  • if not numeric, stop the program and return error message
  • test if x is positive integer
  • if not positive integers, stop the program and return error message
  • create an empty vector called factor_list (indicates the list of factors for the given x)
  • factor_list <- NULL
  • for i = 2 to x (start with testing 2 since 2 is the smallest prime number)
  • while x %% i == 0 ( to test if x is divisible by i)
    • factor_list <- c(factor_list, i)
    • x <- x %/% i (take the resulted quotient of above division to store as x)
  • use is_prime function to test if the factors in factor_list are prime
  • index <- is_prime(factor_list)
  • use index to extract the prime factors of x
  • output: factor_list[index]
#test the get_factors function
get_factors(12)
## [1] 2 2 3
get_factors(1800)
## [1] 2 2 2 3 3 5 5
get_factors(32851)
## [1]  7 13 19 19
get_factors(9587)
## [1] 9587
#test error handling
try(get_factors(-280))
## Error in get_factors(-280) : The input is not positive integer!
try(get_factors(280.75))
## Error in get_factors(280.75) : The input is not positive integer!
